---
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Stage from "~/components/Stage.astro";
import Callout from "~/components/Callout.astro";
---

<Section id="database-authenticity-chain" num="14" title="The authenticity chain">
  <p>
    Privacy and authenticity answer different questions. The privacy proof asks
    what the server can learn from a wallet query. Database authenticity asks
    whether the database root the wallet trusts is tied to Bitcoin history.
  </p>
  <p>
    BitcoinPIR's authenticity story is a chain of small commitments. A PIR
    answer is checked against database Merkle roots; those roots are bound to an
    attested database build anchor; the anchor names a Bitcoin height, block
    hash, and Core-style MuHash; and a separate blockhash-to-MuHash proof ties
    that same tuple to a SEV-SNP-attested computation.
  </p>

  <Stage
    caption="The database claim is not one magic proof. It is a path from a wallet answer to Merkle roots, then to a snapshot anchor, then to a MuHash tree root bound by attestation."
    label="Database authenticity chain"
  >
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 390" role="img"
      aria-label="A vertical chain from PIR answer to database Merkle roots, attested database build, snapshot anchor, BHTM leaf proof, BHTM tree root, SEV-SNP quote, and Bitcoin header-linked stripped-delta stream.">
      {[
        ["1", "PIR answer", "UTXO bytes or verified absence"],
        ["2", "Database Merkle proof", "bucket/onion path to a super-root"],
        ["3", "Attested database build", "roots bound to build evidence"],
        ["4", "Snapshot anchor", "height + block_hash + MuHash"],
        ["5", "BHTM leaf proof", "same tuple under the chunk tree"],
        ["6", "BHTM tree root", "append-only MuHash commitment"],
        ["7", "SEV-SNP quote", "measured proof runner + report data"],
        ["8", "Bitcoin-linked stream", "headers + txid Merkle commitments"],
      ].map(([n, title, detail], i) => {
        const y = 18 + i * 44;
        const accent = i === 3 || i === 6;
        return (
          <g>
            {i > 0 && (
              <line x1="340" y1={y - 10} x2="340" y2={y}
                stroke="var(--fg-muted)" stroke-width="1.2"
                stroke-linecap="round"/>
            )}
            <rect x="74" y={y} width="532" height="34" rx="6"
              fill={accent ? "var(--accent-bg)" : "var(--bg-elev-2)"}
              stroke={accent ? "var(--accent)" : "var(--border)"}/>
            <circle cx="96" cy={y + 17} r="10"
              fill={accent ? "var(--accent)" : "var(--border-strong)"}/>
            <text x="96" y={y + 21} text-anchor="middle" font-size="10"
              font-weight="700" fill="var(--bg)">{n}</text>
            <text x="118" y={y + 15} font-size="11" font-weight="700"
              fill="var(--fg)">{title}</text>
            <text x="118" y={y + 28} font-size="10"
              fill="var(--fg-muted)">{detail}</text>
          </g>
        );
      })}
    </svg>
  </Stage>

  <h3>What this adds</h3>
  <p>
    Section 09 already showed how a wallet verifies returned bins against
    published Merkle roots. This section adds the next question: where did
    those published roots come from, and why should a verifier believe they
    correspond to a Bitcoin snapshot?
  </p>

  <div class="grid-3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
    <div class="backend-card">
      <h4>Database proof</h4>
      <p>
        Binds bucket and onion database super-roots to a snapshot anchor:
        <code>height</code>, <code>block_hash</code>, and Core-display
        <code>MuHash</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="backend-card">
      <h4>BHTM proof</h4>
      <p>
        Shows that the same anchor appears as a leaf under an append-only
        blockhash-to-MuHash chunk tree.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="backend-card">
      <h4>SEV-SNP quote</h4>
      <p>
        Binds the BHTM chunk tree root to a measured reusable proof-runner
        image and checked report signature.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Callout label="Two independent guarantees" kind="ok">
    <p>
      The privacy proof constrains what the server learns from query traffic.
      The authenticity chain constrains what database roots the client accepts.
      They reinforce each other, but they are not the same claim.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</Section>
